rnative to a criminal conviction be a small change with a big impact on children's desistance? -- tInnovative and theoretically informed intervention programmes for children who offend: The Compass Project -- tWhat next for desistance and youth justice? -- tIndex0 aOpen Accessuhttps://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_abf2fd2star  aAvailable open access digitally under CC BY-NC-ND licence. 'Desistance' - understanding how people move away from offending - has become a significant policy focus in recent years, with desistance thinking transplanted from the adult to the youth justice system in England and Wales. This book is the first to critique this approach to justice-involved children, many of whom are yet to fully develop an identity (criminal or otherwise) from which to 'desist'. Featuring voices from academia, policy and practice, this book explores practical approaches to desistance with children in the 'Child First' context. It gives new insights into how children can be supported to move away from offending and proposes reforms to make a meaningful difference to children's lives.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aCriminal behavior, Prediction of. 0aJuvenile delinquencyxPrevention. 0aRecidivismxPrevention. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Criminology.2bisacsh1 aBateman, Tim, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBateman, Tim, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBrierley, Andrew, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBurns, Samantha, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCarr, Steven, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCase, Stephen, econt